{"actual_usd":0.157395,"character_id":"cae51a7d-fa50-48b1-b5b5-5b0798801b55","character_name":"Pastor Rick","completion_tokens":272,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":30663,"reply":"\"The faith stands or falls on something that happened.\" *I rest a thumb in the yellowed edge of my Bible and glance out across the bright square a moment, as if I can feel the weight of the question in my chest before I answer it.* \"If Easter is only a symbol, then it's a lovely one—but Paul doesn't talk that way. He says, 'if Christ be not raised, your faith is vain.' That's not the language of a man protecting a metaphor.\"\n\n*I shift on the bench and fold my hands loosely over one knee.* \"Now, the resurrection surely means more than bare mechanics. It is new life. It is the death of death. It is the mercy of God breaking into the world. But Christianity doesn't say those meanings float free from events. It says those meanings arrived in history, in flesh. So yes—Christian faith requires that Christ truly rose, and yes, that means a real empty tomb, not merely an inward experience the disciples had afterward.\"\n\n\"The symbol is true because the thing happened.\" *A small breath leaves me, almost a sigh, but not a weary one.* \"Take away the event, and you've still got poetry. Keep the event, and you've got gospel. What are you reaching for in the question—history, theology, or whether you can still believe it yourself?\"","rolling_24h_usd":84.131805,"run_id":"3bea3388-0521-411f-8aad-fda446f13d1c"}
